This KM is used to transform Files as a source and output the data in a target File.
The supported datatypes that are natively converted are String (as a java.lang.String), Number (as java.math.BigDecimal) and Date (as java.lang.Date). Any other datatype will be manipulated as a String.
The mappings are to be written taking into account the required datatypes. For instance, if the source column is declared as a Date, it is valid to write a mapping such as: FIL.C1.getTime() which will call the getTime() method of the Date Java class. For example: FIL.C5 + '|' + FIL.C5 FIL.C5.toLowerCase() Long.parseLong(FIL.C5.substring(1))+10 FIL.C4.doubleValue()*2
Caution: avoid declaring a datatype as a Number or a Date if you don't need native transformations on it because it takes additionnal time to have the data converted into the native datatype.
This KM supports Filters that can be written in the form of a Java expression returning true or false. For example: (FIL.C1.doubleValue() > 10) && (FIL.C2.length()>5)
Number of Threads that are to be used when processing the File. As a best practice, you shouldn't set this value higher than the number of CPUs (or cores) available on the machine.
Set this option to true if you want the result to be appended to the target file. If set to no, the content will be overwritten.
Optionnaly specify an encoding for the Target file. Leave blank to use the machine's default encoding.
Enter a valid location for a jdk 1.6. Examples: $ODI_JAVA_HOME on Unix %ODI_JAVA_HOME% on Windows /usr/local/bin/jdk1.6
JAR or ZIP file of the JDBC Driver
Use this option to specify the JAR or ZIP file(s) of the JDBC driver to be used when loading the target database.
You can specify additionnal JVM Options to be passed when calling the JVM. For example: -Djava.security.egd=file:///dev/urandom
Name of a target Numeric Column
Specify the name of a target column of type Numeric which will be used to split the data into chunks to be processed in parallel. The option is mandatory is NB_THREADS > 1
Force the usage of a flow table

Set this option to true if the source data is first to be copied in a staging table. This is particularly useful when using multiple threads if the source data keeps changing during the unload process, overwise some data in the target file will be out of sync.

/* This function is used to generate the required code to declare the formatters that will be used on each output field.
The choice of the formatter is based on the datatype of the target column */
void createOutputFormaters() {
	String doubleQuote = "" + '"';
	<% if ("D".equals(odiRef.getTargetTable("FILE_FORMAT"))) {%>
		/* For delimited files, we call the constructor without specifying the length of the data in order to avoid useless padding of the output String */
		<%= odiRef.getColList("if (\u0022DATE\u0022.equals(\u0022[DEST_DT]\u0022)) { out.println(\u0022OdiDateFormatOUT out[COL_NAME]Formatter = new OdiDateFormatOUT(\u0022 + doubleQuote + \u0022[COL_FORMAT]\u0022 + doubleQuote + \u0022, myStringUtils);\u0022);} else if (\u0022NUMERIC\u0022.equals(\u0022[DEST_DT]\u0022)) { out.println(\u0022OdiNumberFormatOUT out[COL_NAME]Formatter = new OdiNumberFormatOUT(\u0022 + doubleQuote + \u0022[COL_DEC_SEP]\u0022 + doubleQuote + \u0022, myStringUtils);\u0022);} else { out.println(\u0022OdiStringFormatOUT out[COL_NAME]Formatter = new OdiStringFormatOUT(myStringUtils);\u0022);}", "\n\t") %>
	<% } else { %>
		/* For fixed files, we call the constructor with the specication of the length of the data in order to pad the output String with spaces if needed */
		<%= odiRef.getColList("if (\u0022DATE\u0022.equals(\u0022[DEST_DT]\u0022)) { out.println(\u0022OdiDateFormatOUT out[COL_NAME]Formatter = new OdiDateFormatOUT(\u0022 + doubleQuote + \u0022[COL_FORMAT]\u0022 + doubleQuote + \u0022, [BYTES], myStringUtils);\u0022);} else if (\u0022NUMERIC\u0022.equals(\u0022[DEST_DT]\u0022)) { out.println(\u0022OdiNumberFormatOUT out[COL_NAME]Formatter = new OdiNumberFormatOUT(\u0022 + doubleQuote + \u0022[COL_DEC_SEP]\u0022 + doubleQuote + \u0022, [BYTES], myStringUtils);\u0022);} else { out.println(\u0022OdiStringFormatOUT out[COL_NAME]Formatter = new OdiStringFormatOUT([BYTES], myStringUtils);\u0022);}", "\n\t") %>
	<% } %>
}

/* This function is used to generate the required code to retrieve the data from the database and call the corresponding formatters.
The choice of the method to retrieve the data is based on the datatype of the target column */
void useOutputFormaters() {
	String doubleQuote = "" + '"';
	int i = 1;
	<% if ("D".equals(odiRef.getTargetTable("FILE_FORMAT"))) {%>
		<%= odiRef.getColList("if (\u0022DATE\u0022.equals(\u0022[DEST_DT]\u0022)) { out.println(\u0022out[COL_NAME]Formatter.format((Date) myResultset.getTimestamp(\u0022 + i + \u0022), myStringBuilder);\u0022);} else if (\u0022NUMERIC\u0022.equals(\u0022[DEST_DT]\u0022)) { out.println(\u0022out[COL_NAME]Formatter.format(myResultset.getDouble(\u0022 + i + \u0022), myStringBuilder);\u0022);} else { out.println(\u0022out[COL_NAME]Formatter.format(myResultset.getString(\u0022 + i + \u0022), myStringBuilder);\u0022);}", "\n\ti++;\n\tout.println(\u0022myStringBuilder.append(trgRecordSeparator);\u0022);\n\t") %>
	<% } else { %>
		<%= odiRef.getColList("if (\u0022DATE\u0022.equals(\u0022[DEST_DT]\u0022)) { out.println(\u0022out[COL_NAME]Formatter.format((Date) myResultset.getTimestamp(\u0022 + i + \u0022), myStringBuilder);\u0022);} else if (\u0022NUMERIC\u0022.equals(\u0022[DEST_DT]\u0022)) { out.println(\u0022out[COL_NAME]Formatter.format(myResultset.getDouble(\u0022 + i + \u0022), myStringBuilder);\u0022);} else { out.println(\u0022out[COL_NAME]Formatter.format(myResultset.getString(\u0022 + i + \u0022), myStringBuilder);\u0022);}", "\n\ti++;") %>
	<% } %>

}
